  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">The reorganization provisions, on the<BR ALIGN='left'/>other hand, provide relief where the<BR ALIGN='left'/>business of a corporation will be<BR ALIGN='left'/>continued by the shareholders but with<BR ALIGN='left'/>changes in the corporate form. These<BR ALIGN='left'/>provisions provide for the<BR ALIGN='left'/>nonrecognition of gain or loss to the<BR ALIGN='left'/>extent the shareholders exchange stocks<BR ALIGN='left'/>or securities of the old corporation for<BR ALIGN='left'/>those of the new. I.R.C. § 354, 26<BR ALIGN='left'/>U.S.C.A. § 354. Property received in the<BR ALIGN='left'/>exchange other than stocks or<BR ALIGN='left'/>securities, however, call &quot;boot,&quot; is<BR ALIGN='left'/>generally viewed as equivalent to<BR ALIGN='left'/>dividends and is taxed as such, at least<BR ALIGN='left'/>to the extent it represents<BR ALIGN='left'/>undistributed earnings and profits of<BR ALIGN='left'/>the corporation. I.R.C. § 356, 26<BR ALIGN='left'/>U.S.C.A. § 356. See generally Davant v.<BR ALIGN='left'/>Commissioner, 366 F.2d 874, 882-87 (5th<BR ALIGN='left'/>Cir. 1966).</TD></TR>
